Here is my pre-workout mobility routine that I had posted on my story a couple of weeks ago. A bunch of you guys wanted me to make it a permanent post so that you can refer to it in the future so here you go!
-
I am not a mobility expert by any means. As you can see, I don’t actually know the names of any of these movements. As I got older, I noticed I that I needed to warm up more and more prior to my workouts to feel ready and started incorporating some movements that I found helpful. I’m not trying to be a yoga expert. I’m just trying to loosen myself up to avoid injury and this has certainly helped me with that.
-
Feel free to give some of these a shot as well as others that you find work well for you. Depending on the areas that are tight for you, there may be some other exercises you want to include. Conversely, you may be able to skip some of the ones I do if you don’t find it helpful for you.
-
If you are struggling with 𝐜𝐚𝐥𝐜𝐮𝐥𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐧𝐠 your 𝐦𝐚𝐜𝐫𝐨𝐬, setting up 𝐲𝐨𝐮𝐫 𝐝𝐢𝐞𝐭, and designing an 𝐞𝐟𝐟𝐞𝐜𝐭𝐢𝐯𝐞 𝐰𝐨𝐫𝐤𝐨𝐮𝐭 𝐫𝐨𝐮𝐭𝐢𝐧𝐞, check out my 𝐞𝐛𝐨𝐨𝐤 by clicking the 𝐥𝐢𝐧𝐤 𝐢𝐧 𝐦𝐲 𝐛𝐢𝐨💪🏼.
-
If you’re interested in working with me 1 on 1 for a custom plan tailored to your goals, send me an email for more information on online coaching.

Here is my most recent pull hypertrophy workout that I posted on my story a few days ago as I was doing it. For those of you who didn’t know, I always post my workouts on my story as I do them.
-
This is my second of two pull workouts for the week. The first one is with heavier weight and fewer reps. I posted that one a couple of weeks ago. My second one is with less weight and more reps.

Today’s workout was:

Lat Pulldowns: 4 sets of 10-12
One Arm Machine Rows: 4 sets of 10
Chest Supported Tbar Rows: 3 sets of 12-15
Rear Delt Flyes: 3 sets of 12
Hammer Curls: 3 sets of 20-25

Calves are one of the toughest body parts to develop. Part of the reason is they are fairly dependent on your genetics (to a higher degree than most muscles in my opinion) and they also get trained incorrectly. I'd like to think I have pretty decent calves so I'll share 3 tips on what has helped me the most. Number 3 is the most crucial and is what I will discuss in this video.
-
1. Frequency: Train your calves at least 2-3 times per week with 4-8 sets each workout. You can even do calves at the end of every single workout. Your calves are used to a heavy workload since you've been walking on them your whole life. They can handle the work and you won't be overtraining them.
-
2. Form: Make sure you are actually using your calves when you do calf raises. Slow and controlled on the way down and pause for a second at the top. No bouncing or using momentum. Your calves are a small muscle and it's very easy to cheat and take the emphasis off them by letting your ego get in the way. People care about how much you bench, not how much you calf raise.
-
3. **Huge Drop Sets**: This is the single technique that has helped my calves the most. On your last set of calf raises, choose a weight you can hit for 8-12 reps. Do a drop set and on the drop set count 3 second negatives and pause for a second at the top of each rep. Go to failure and then do another drop set doing the same thing. Do 3 or 4 of these drop sets with the 3 second negatives and 1 second pause at the top with each set to failure. The set should take 2-4 minutes, your calves will be burning, and it will be the sickest pump you've ever gotten. Do this at least twice per week and your calves will grow.

ONE HEALTHY MEAL by @apfau
-
I always smile a little when I’m out for dinner and I overhear someone say something along the lines of “I’m so healthy. I ordered a salad.” While making a healthy choice is certainly a good start, one healthy choice does not suddenly mean you are living a healthy lifestyle. On the opposite end of the spectrum, eating a crappy meal every once in a while doesn’t mean you’re unhealthy. Living a healthy or unhealthy lifestyle isn’t dictated by a few decisions. Rather, you should aim to make better decisions more often than not over the long run. You don’t need to eat perfectly all the time but you can certainly improve your lifestyle by slowly eating better over time. Swipe left for a helpful post by @grantgirsky reminding you that you should aim for consistency and not necessarily perfection.

This is an example of a pull strength workout. A pull workout is where you target your back, biceps, traps, and rear delts. This workout would fit in as one of your pull days days in a push/pull/legs program.

Strength workouts are generally 3-6 reps on the more compound movements (like deadlifts) but could be more like 6-10 reps on some of the isolation exercises (doing 3-6 reps on something like face pulls would be awkward). node.text:
MAKE WEIGHT GAIN EASIER by @apfau
-
Gaining weight simply requires eating in a caloric surplus which means consuming more calories than your body burns each day. For a lot of people, including myself, gaining weight is too easy. However, hardgainers find it difficult to consume enough calories each day which makes gaining weight a challenge.
-
If you’re struggling to eat enough, you should try to eat calorie dense foods. Nut butters, nuts, and seeds are extremely calorie dense. The calories can add up quickly without filling you up too much. Certain fruits like bananas are also fairly calorie dense and can be an easy way to eat enough carbs. Peanut butter and jelly sandwiches are also calorie dense and of course, who doesn’t love PB & J?
-
Oil is the most calorie dense food (if you want to call it a food) you can eat. For that reason, I suggest avoiding it for fat loss but it’s great if you need easy calories. You can cook with it or even add it to protein shakes which will add calories that you can barely even notice.
-
Liquid calories are easier to consume than eating solid food which is why making your own weight gain shakes is a good idea. You could buy a mass gainer if you find one with good ingredients or you can make your own with ingredients of your choice. A common example would include milk, protein powder, oats, peanut butter, and bananas.
-
If you’re interested in working with me for a 𝘤𝘶𝘴𝘵𝘰𝘮𝘪𝘻𝘦𝘥 𝗺𝗲𝗮𝗹 𝗽𝗹𝗮𝗻 and 𝘄𝗼𝗿𝗸𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗿𝗼𝘂𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗲 tailored to your goals, click the 𝗹𝗶𝗻𝗸 𝗶𝗻 𝗺𝘆 𝗯𝗶𝗼 to get started. I will also give you my 𝗲𝗯𝗼𝗼𝗸 for 𝙁𝙍𝙀𝙀 when you sign up💪.

node.text:
NO SWEAT NO PROBLEM by @apfau
-
A common misconception is that sweating burns fat and if you’re not sweating then you can’t be having an effective workout. Sweating by itself does NOT burn extra calories. It’s simply your body’s attempt to cool itself down as your body temperature increases. Sweat may be an indication that you’re working hard but you can also sweat just by eating spicy food or sitting in the sun.
-
However, chances are that if you’re not sweating, especially during cardio or a leg workout, then you probably aren’t working that hard but it is common to not sweat much on upper body days especially if the gym is cold. Some people break a sweat a lot more easily than others as well. The leaner I am, the less I sweat.

DIPS by @apfau
-
Dips are awesome for triceps and lower chest. It’s common for people who struggle with dips to compensate by shortening their range of motion, flaring their elbows, and hunching forward. node.text:
INTENSITY TECHNIQUES by @apfau
-
Accumulating enough volume and intensity during your workouts is key to making progress. However, time constraints often make this a bit difficult to achieve. Here are some volume/intensity techniques that you can use in your training.
-
(1) SUPERSETS: A superset is when you perform two exercises right after the other without resting in between. I personally utilize supersets on my upper body days simply to save time. Rather than doing nothing while resting between sets, you simply do another exercise. You should select two exercises that do not work the same muscles though (such as pairing back with chest or biceps/triceps).
-
(2) GIANT SETS: A giant set is the same as a superset but with more than two exercises. The same concept applies. I don’t utilize these as much as it’s difficult to pair more than two exercises which don’t overlap with the targeted muscles. However, one that I like to do is leg extensions, calf raises, and leg curls at the end of leg day.
-
(3) DROP SETS: A drop set is where you drop the weight after your last set on a particular exercise and bang out a few more reps. I personally love these and utilize them on the last exercise for each body part on hypertrophy days. Drop sets are a great way to add extra volume and intensity to your workout without adding much extra time.
-
(4) REST PAUSE: This is where you rest for about 10-20 seconds after your last rep on your last set and then squeeze out a few more reps. I used to utilize these more several years ago when strength was one of my goals since it’s a good way to allow yourself to recruit more muscle fibers and do more reps with heavier weight. However, this one can be a bit dangerous if you’re a beginner.

node.text:
MACROS 101 by @apfau
-
Calories are made up of macros. Macros stands for macronutrients. There are only three macronutrients. They are protein, carbs, and fat. Protein and carbs each have 4 calories per gram and fat has 9 calories per gram. So, when you see the total calorie count of any food, those numbers aren't magically created. They are simply all of the macros added up to give you a total amount of calories.
-
Carbs are useful for many reasons. The primary one is energy and performance. They will help fuel your workouts and provide you with energy throughout the day. Examples include: bread, pasta, rice, oatmeal, potatoes, fruits, veggies.
-
Fat also has many benefits. One of the important ones is that it helps regulate hormones. If your fat is too low for too long, your testosterone levels will likely take a hit. Some examples are avocados, nut butters, oils, seeds, nuts.
-
Protein is the building block for muscle recovery. As we work out and break down our muscles, protein is needed to help our muscles repair themselves and grow. Examples include: meat, eggs, fish, Greek yogurt, whey, cottage cheese.
-
So, should you track calories or macros? Well, if you track macros, you're already tracking calories whether you realized it or not. If you only track calories, then you're probably a lot closer to tracking macros than you may have realized. While overall calories are most important for gaining or losing weight, there is an added benefit to having those calories be comprised of the right macros for your body. STRETCH MARKS by @apfau
-
This is photo is from 2007. That was the year I tried to gain weight as fast as possible. I only cared about the number on the scale increasing and gained about 50 lbs in 6 months. I ended up with awful stretch marks down my arms. I didn’t realize they were permanent so I kept bulking and made them even worse. At that point, I tried every cream, oil, and device to try to get rid of them with no luck. It was devastating. I was finally somewhat confident with my physique in T-shirt’s but the stretch marks were so embarrassing that I wouldn’t go anywhere without being covered up anyway.
-
This picture doesn’t come close to showing how bad they actually were because I refused to take pictures at the time. This is the only one I could find.
-
It’s easy to say that they are “battle scars” and to be proud but that’s not how I felt. I honestly wished I could just go back to having no muscle and no stretch marks. For beginners, stretch marks are usually not a thought or consideration. At first, we are so obsessed with gaining muscle that the idea that our skin wouldn’t be able to keep up with our gains almost sounds like something to strive for rather than something to prevent. However, stretch marks can be devastating and unfortunately, most people don’t become aware of this until it’s too late.
-
Today, 14 years later, I still have them but they faded considerably and you probably wouldn’t notice them unless you’re looking for them. There is no full proof way to prevent them but there are certain things you can do. The most important one is to never gain or lose weight too quickly. If you gain 2-3 pounds per week like I did, you’ll most likely get them. My other two recommendations are to drink enough water and moisturize daily. Once you have them, there is not much you can do and unfortunately, most people don’t even begin to think about them until they already have them.
-

FIX MAN BOOBS by @apfau
-
First, let me define “man boobs” as having excess fat on your chest. It can sometimes be confused with gynocomastia which is a hormonal issue but that is not what I am addressing here. However, more often than not, people who think they have gyno just have excess fat around their chest.
-
The first mistake people usually make is trying to spot reduce fat around their chest by doing high rep chest training. You cannot choose where your body burns fat first. Swipe left for a great graphic by @roballenfitness which illustrates spot reduction a bit further. Doing high reps on chest exercises does not burn extra chest fat. Instead, you should work your chest 2-3 times a week with resistance training and focus on building your chest which in combination with losing fat, will improve the overall appearance of your chest over time.
-
A second mistake is relying on fat burners and other supplements to burn the fat. There are no safe, legal supplements that will make any noticeable difference when it comes to your fat loss results if your diet and training aren’t on point. Instead, focus on a conservative caloric deficit with enough protein.
-
Lastly, results don’t happen overnight and you should not try to rush the process. Don’t overly restrict calories and don’t go crazy with the cardio. You should use cardio as a tool to burn additional calories to aid in fat loss but you should do it in addition to weight training. Like I said above, building chest muscle will help the appearance of your chest and most importantly, it takes time.

-
If you’re interested in working with me for a 𝘤𝘶𝘴𝘵𝘰𝘮𝘪𝘻𝘦𝘥 𝗺𝗲𝗮𝗹 𝗽𝗹𝗮𝗻 and 𝘄𝗼𝗿𝗸𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗿𝗼𝘂𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗲 tailored to your goals, click the 𝗹𝗶𝗻𝗸 𝗶𝗻 𝗺𝘆 𝗯𝗶𝗼 to get started. I will also give you my 𝗲𝗯𝗼𝗼𝗸 for 𝙁𝙍𝙀𝙀 when you sign up💪.
-
I am a proponent of flexible dieting but the concept of being able to fit some unhealthy foods into your diet has caused many people to believe that all carbs are equal. They definitely are not.
-
Soda, candy, and chips have no nutritional value and are loaded with sugar. They won’t do anything to satisfy your hunger and will probably make you hungrier instead. Fruits, veggies, whole grain breads, rice, potatoes, and pasta contain a bunch more nutrients as well as fiber. They are better for you, will provide more sustained energy, and will fill you up.
-
If you want to enjoy some candy in moderation, that is fine (although I’d personally prefer cookies if I’m fitting in a treat 😁). Just don’t convince yourself that you can hit your carbs with anything under the mentality that “a carb is a carb” because even if you hit your macros, getting most of your carbs from junk is not healthy.
